philosophical vertigo of Paradiso not as a critic but from the point of view of a faithful, assiduous, perceptive, sometimes perplexed, and sometimes worshipful reader. Cacciari's analysis shows once more that Dante does not belong to the past. Dante creates his own age and stays with us whenever we wish to follow his path.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Mrz 2024) 4aArea Studies : Italian Studies. 4aPhilosophy : Philosophy. 4aReligion and Spirituality : Religion and Politics. 7aPHILOSOPHY / History & Surveys / Medieval.2bisacsh1 aCarrera, Alessandro, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarrera, Alessandro, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMobili, Giorgio, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package 2022z978311149185140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143848690140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438486901423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438486901/original  a978-3-11-149185-1  SUNY Press eBook Package 2022b2022  aGBV-deGruyter-alles